snippet.title: FAM punishes Selangor FC after VVIP and fans turn violent
snippet.description:
A VVIP threw a water bottle while fans turned rowdy during a FA Cup match at the MBPJ Stadium on Oct 29.

The FAM Disciplinary Committee has found Selangor guilty of fan violence, VVIP misconduct, vandalism and organisational negligence.

As punishment, Selangor were fined RM100,000, and must also play two FA Cup home matches behind closed doors.

Video clips of the incident went viral, showing smoke from firecrackers, broken seats, and fans clashing. One clip allegedly shows a drink container being thrown from an VIP area, fueling public outrage.

FAM's Disciplinary Committee chairman, Datuk Baljit Singh Sidhu, said in a statement today that Selangor FC supporters carried out the burning of firecrackers, with approximately two explosions seen and heard being thrown towards the Negri Sembilan FC supporters' seating area.

snippet.title: Langkawi migrant boat capsize: 21 bodies recovered so far; search expanded again
snippet.description:
Search and rescue (SAR) teams have expanded their coverage to 272.78 square nautical miles as the operation entered its third day to locate some undocumented immigrants still missing after the boat tragedy near the Malaysia-Thailand maritime border.

The joint mission between Malaysian and Thai authorities has so far recovered 21 bodies — 12 in Malaysian waters and nine in Thailand — while all 13 survivors were found on the Malaysian side.

A Malaysian Maritime Enforcement Agency spokesman said the operation resumed at 7.30am today, supported by five MMEA vessels and an aircraft.

Also deployed are assets from the marine police, Royal Malaysian Navy, Fisheries Department, Fire and Rescue Department and the Civil Defence Force.

The tragedy comes amid the ongoing conflict in Myanmar that continues to force Rohingya families onto overcrowded, unseaworthy boats in pursuit of safety.

snippet.title: Malaysian link to Langkawi migrant boat tragedy
snippet.description:
Malaysian nationals are suspected of collaborating with a cross-border human trafficking syndicate behind the Langkawi migrant boat tragedy. Police are expanding their investigation to identify local operatives who may have facilitated the deadly voyage. 

Evidence gathered includes Malaysian-linked phone contacts, suspicious behaviour from survivors, and details on how the journey was organised. 

Kedah police chief Datuk Adzli Abu Shah revealed that the migrants, mostly Rohingya, had paid around RM13,500 to escape Myanmar in hopes of a better life in Malaysia. 

Eighteen people, including a 5-year-old girl, are confirmed dead, while 13 survivors are in custody. 

Two Bangladeshi men have also drawn suspicion. 

Langkawi police chief Khairul Azhar Nurudin confirmed that phone numbers seized from survivors point to possible Malaysian involvement.

snippet.title: For polyglot sensation Yuji, language is a window to many worlds
snippet.description:
What began as casual street interviews has turned Yuji Beleza into an unlikely ambassador of language and culture.

The 27-year-old Japanese-Irish polyglot says learning a language is more than memorising words — it’s a doorway into someone’s world.

With more than 13 million followers, Yuji has transformed that belief into a global phenomenon.

His viral clips — where he approaches strangers and speaks their native tongue — have won hearts across continents.

Born in Kyoto to a multilingual family, Yuji speaks five languages fluently — Russian, German, Turkish, English and Japanese — and can chat in up to 30 more.

His philosophy is simple: practise constantly, and don’t be afraid to speak.

Yuji is expected to visit Malaysia next year — and he already has a message for fans here: “Saya sayang awak.”

snippet.title: Thai cops seize pistols from ex footballer linked to Malaysian's fatal shooting
snippet.description:
Thai police seized two pistols from an ex-footballer arrested over the fatal shooting of a Malaysian in Golok on Saturday.

Sungai Golok police chief Colonel Jetsadawit Inpraphan said the 31-year-old suspect was arrested yesterday evening.

He added that they also seized two guns believed to be used in the killing of the 33-year-old Malaysian.

The suspect, who is from Bereng, Sungai Golok, is expected to be charged with several offences, including murder, illegal possession of firearms and ammunition, and carrying firearms in public without a permit or reasonable cause.

The suspect, a former Kelantan football player, has both Thai and Malaysian passports.

He is being held at the Sungai Golok police station and will be remanded.

snippet.title: 60-year-old, one-tonne crocodile caught in Tawau river after near attack
snippet.description:
A giant crocodile believed to be around 60 years old and weighing nearly one tonne was captured at Kampung Pangkalan Asli, Merotai Besar, in Tawau.

The Sabah Wildlife Department said the 5.4m reptile had been threatening villagers who often fished by the riverside. 

It was caught along with three other crocodiles after traps were set.

snippet.title: Hurricane Melissa batters Jamaica, unleashing deadly floods and destruction
snippet.description:
Hurricane Melissa made landfall in Jamaica on Tuesday, tearing through the island with sustained winds of 300 kilometres per hour.

The storm knocked out power, uprooted trees, and triggered flash floods and landslides, making it the most powerful hurricane to ever strike Jamaica.

Seven deaths have been reported across Jamaica, Haiti, and the Dominican Republic, with damage still being assessed as communication remains down.

Melissa has since moved off Jamaica and is heading toward Cuba and the Bahamas, but its impact continues to be felt.

Jamaica’s climate change minister described the situation as catastrophic, with flooded homes and severely damaged infrastructure.

Health authorities have warned residents to watch for displaced crocodiles due to rising water levels.

Scientists say human-driven climate change is intensifying storms like Melissa, increasing their destructive potential.

Relief efforts are underway, with the UN preparing to airlift supplies once conditions allow.

snippet.title: Bodies pile up as deadly Rio drug raids leave 64 dead in ‘war-like’ scenes
snippet.description:
At least 64 people were killed in Rio de Janeiro on Tuesday during the city’s largest-ever police operation targeting drug traffickers.

Around 2,500 heavily armed officers stormed two northern favelas—Complexo da Penha and Complexo do Alemao—backed by helicopters, drones, and armoured vehicles.

The raids aimed to stop the expansion of Brazil’s Red Command gang, but quickly escalated into war-like scenes near Rio’s international airport.

Residents reported drones dropping explosives, shops shuttered, and traffic ground to a halt.

Among the dead were 60 suspected gang members and four police officers.

Human rights groups and UN officials condemned the violence, calling for investigations into the deadly tactics used in Brazil’s marginalised communities.

Critics say these operations treat favelas as enemy territory and fail to dismantle criminal networks.

snippet.title: Bring back GST after next election, says Ong
snippet.description:
Bringing back Goods and Services Tax (GST) after the next general election could be just what Malaysia needs to fix its finances, said policy analyst Prof Ong Kian Ming.

He said the move would help refill government coffers as debt payments and spending on salaries and pensions continue to climb, taking up more than 60 per cent of next year’s budget.

Ong suggested reintroducing GST gradually, possibly in 2026, and starting with a lower rate so it is easier on consumers.

PwC Malaysia tax partner Ang Wei Liang agreed the idea has merit, saying the previous GST collapsed due to trust issues and refund delays, but the new e-invoicing system could make a smoother comeback possible this time.

snippet.title: Quiet supersonic X-59 jet soars over California desert in first test flight
snippet.description:
NASA’s supersonic X-59 jet has completed its first test flight over the Southern California desert, marking a breakthrough in quiet, high-speed aviation.

Built by Lockheed Martin, the experimental aircraft took off from Palmdale and landed safely at Edwards Air Force Base, escorted by a NASA chase plane.

The X-59 is engineered to break the sound barrier with minimal noise, replacing the traditional sonic boom with a softer “sonic thump.”

On its debut flight, the jet reached 230 miles per hour at 12,000 feet, with future tests expected to push it past Mach 1.

NASA has invested over US$518 million in the project since 2018, aiming to revolutionise commercial air travel over land.

The aircraft was recently named 2025’s “Coolest Thing Made in California” and will help redefine sound regulations for supersonic flight.

snippet.description:

snippet.title: Record floods leave 10 dead, turn Vietnam's Hoi An into canals
snippet.description:
Major flooding has killed at least 10 people in central Vietnam this week, turning Hoi An’s historic streets into waist-deep canals.

A record 1.7 metres of rain fell in just 24 hours, submerging homes, shops, and roads across five provinces.

Residents steered boats through the UNESCO-listed town, with some saying they’ve never seen flooding this severe.

The Thu Bon river reached its highest level in 60 years, surpassing the 1964 record.

More than 128,000 homes were inundated, 5,000 hectares of crops destroyed, and 16,000 cattle lost.

Rescuers used drones to deliver supplies to stranded travellers, while landslides blocked key routes between Danang and Quang Ngai.

Forecasters warn water levels remain “alarming,” even as they begin to recede.

Scientists say climate change is intensifying extreme weather, with Vietnam reporting 187 deaths or missing persons from natural disasters this year.

snippet.title: RM6.2mil car smuggling bust: Customs seizes 47 luxury vehicles
snippet.description:
The Kelantan Customs Department has seized 47 untaxed vehicles worth over RM6.2 million, including duties, in operations conducted between January and Oct 16 this year.

State director Wan Jamal Abdul Salam Wan Long said the vehicles, comprising various makes and models of luxury cars, were believed to have been smuggled in from neighbouring countries without complying with import and tax regulations.

Among the confiscated vehicles were a Volkswagen Beetle, Volvo S80, BMW 325i, Maserati Ghibli, Honda Jazz, Toyota Vellfire and Mercedes-Benz. They were being sold for between RM53,000 and RM185,000 — around 35 per cent to 40 per cent below market value.

He added that the seizures were made in Kelantan, Kuala Lumpur and Johor through a series of intelligence-led operations and enforcement efforts, including along border areas.

The case is being investigated under Section 135(1)(d) of the Customs Act 1967, which carries a fine of between 10 and 20 times the value of the goods — or between RM50,000 and RM500,000, whichever is higher — or imprisonment for up to five years, or both, for a first offence.

The family home of Singapore’s founding Prime Minister, Lee Kuan Yew, at 38 Oxley Road, has been earmarked for preservation as a national monument.

Today, the government announced plans to gazette the site following an assessment by the National Heritage Board’s advisory panel, which deemed it historically significant and nationally important.

This would prohibit any redevelopment for residential, commercial, or private use.

The issue resurfaced in October 2024 after the death of their sister, Dr Lee Wei Ling, who had been living in the home since Lee Kuan Yew’s passing in 2015.

Lee Hsien Yang later applied to demolish the property, prompting a formal review by the authorities.

The National Heritage Board concluded its assessment in late 2025, recommending preservation due to the site’s historic merit.

Several items at the eatery were damaged, but no serious injuries were reported.

snippet.title: Blaze destroys four textile warehouses in Sungai Buloh
snippet.description:
A massive fire destroyed four textile storage warehouses at Kampung Desa Aman near Sungai Buloh this morning.

The Selangor Fire and Rescue Department received a distress call at 9.50am and arrived at the scene by 10.03am.

Flames had already engulfed four adjoining warehouse lots, each measuring roughly 75 by 25 feet.

Three of the lots were almost completely destroyed, while the fourth sustained minor damage.

The warehouses, classified as Class C buildings, were used to store fabrics and textile materials.

A total of 33 firefighters from four stations were deployed, supported by fire engines, water tankers, a utility vehicle, and an Emergency Medical Rescue Services unit.

Six people suffered breathing difficulties due to smoke inhalation and were treated at the scene. No fatalities were reported.

Firefighting operations continued into late morning to fully extinguish the blaze and prevent it from spreading.

snippet.title: Typhoon Kalmaegi slams central Philippines, warnings of 'life-threatening' surges
snippet.description:
Typhoon Kalmaegi intensified as it made landfall in the central Philippines on Tuesday, bringing life-threatening conditions across the Visayas region.

With sustained winds of 150 kilometres per hour and gusts reaching 205, the storm—locally named Tino—is expected to cross the Visayas and move into the South China Sea by Wednesday.

The weather bureau PAGASA said the typhoon, combined with a shear line, triggered heavy rain and strong winds across the region.

While some weakening is expected due to terrain, Kalmaegi is forecast to maintain typhoon strength throughout its passage.

Over 160 flights have been cancelled, and vessels were urged to seek shelter or remain in port.

In Southern Leyte, evacuations were carried out in low-lying and coastal areas.

Authorities warned of storm surges exceeding three metres in parts of the central Philippines and Mindanao.

The country, which faces around 20 tropical storms annually, is still recovering from recent disasters, including September’s Super Typhoon Ragasa.

snippet.description:

FIFA confirmed that both FAM and the players have been notified and have 10 days to request a full written judgment.

snippet.title: FAM calls FIFA battle a 'major war' to defend Malaysian football
snippet.description:

Acting president Datuk Yusoff Mahadi described the legal battle as a “major war” to defend the country’s football reputation.

FAM will submit all necessary documents and evidence to CAS in an effort to overturn the sanctions.

FAM’s internal appeal was rejected, but the association says it will fully utilise the 21-day window to mount its case.

Yusoff acknowledged the process may be long and costly but said FAM is committed to protecting Malaysia’s football image.

The 32-year-old former youth and sports minister is taking on the challenge to secure a pledged RM1 million donation for the people of Muar if he successfully completes the race.

The challenge was issued by local fashion brand Prima Valet, which promised the incentive should he finish the triathlon — consisting of a 3.8km swim, 180km cycling leg and 42.2km run — within the stipulated time.

In a post shared on his Facebook and TikTok accounts last night, Syed Saddiq said that the challenge was not for personal gain, but to help his constituents.

To demonstrate his commitment, Syed Saddiq shared clips of his intensive training and even shaved his head, joking that the move could save him three seconds in the race.

snippet.title: Businessman re-arrested in Terengganu over RM35,000 land fraud
snippet.description:
A businessman has been re-arrested by police to assist in an investigation into a land transaction fraud case in Terengganu.

The Besut magistrate's court had previously granted bail of RM6,000 to entrepreneur Datuk Mohammad Azlan Abdullah after he pleaded not guilty to a charge of mischief for allegedly damaging a Perodua Bezza car.

However, Terengganu police chief Datuk Khairi Khairudin said the suspect was re-arrested by the Commercial Crime Investigation Department to assist further investigations into a land transaction fraud case involving a retired teacher.

According to Khairi, the case is being investigated under Section 420 of the Penal Code, which carries a maximum punishment of 10 years' imprisonment, whipping, and a fine if convicted.

He advised the public to remain vigilant when conducting any land or property transactions.

snippet.title: Che'gu Bard cleared of defamation charge against the King
snippet.description:
Port Dickson Bersatu division chief Badrul Hisham Shaharin has been acquitted by the Sessions Court of a charge of defaming His Majesty Sultan Ibrahim, King of Malaysia.

Judge Norma Ismail ruled the prosecution had failed to establish a prima facie case against Badrul Hisham, 46, who is better known as Che'gu Bard.

Badrul Hisham was visibly relieved upon hearing the verdict. Before leaving the dock, he turned to the judge and thanked Yang Arif.

Last April, Badrul Hisham claimed trial to making the defamatory statements against the Yang di-Pertuan Agong.

The charge, framed under Section 500 of the Penal Code, carries a maximum two-year jail term, a fine, or both upon conviction.

snippet.title: King Charles strips Andrew of royal titles, Windsor home
snippet.description:
King Charles III will strip his younger brother Andrew of his royal titles and oust him from his long-term residence on the Windsor estate, the palace said on Thursday, the latest fallout to hit the scandal-plagued royal over the Jeffrey Epstein affair.

Buckingham Palace said that Prince Andrew will now be known as Andrew Mountbatten Windsor, adding that Charles had begun the formal process to remove all his brother's titles.

Andrew has also been told to move out of his long-time home on Windsor Castle's sprawling grounds, and he will move "to alternative private accommodation" as soon as possible.

The announcement followed a torrent of outrage at renewed accusations of sexual assault made by one of Jeffrey Epstein's main accusers against the 65-year-old, who has denied the charges.

The palace said that these censures are deemed necessary, notwithstanding the fact that he continues to deny the allegations against him.

snippet.title: Landslide hits Balik Pulau: Jalan Tun Sardon closed to all traffic
snippet.description:
A landslide struck Jalan Tun Sardon near Bukit Baru in Balik Pulau around 5pm today, prompting a full road closure.

A video circulating online shows a car passing moments before the slope gave way.

Authorities have instructed stranded vehicles to turn back and use alternative routes, while urging all motorists to avoid the affected stretch.

Emergency response teams are currently on-site to assess the damage and ensure public safety.

No injuries or casualties have been reported.

The incident follows several days of heavy rainfall in Penang, which also saw multiple reports of fallen trees.

Officials have shared images of the landslide and are monitoring the situation closely.
